CVC set to return with higher offer for Betfair
A consortium led by CVC Capital Partners is poised to return with an offer slightly less than £10 a share for gambling exchange Betfair.
Shares in Betfair, which floated in October 2010 at £13 a share, closed on Friday at 898p, up 2.63pc, valuing the company at £936m. Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Nathalie Thomas, and James Quinn
10:00PM BST 11 May 2013
Follow Comments
The private equity group, which is working with two major Betfair shareholders — Richard Koch and Antony Ball — is understood to have sounded out investors over a revised approach ahead of a takeover panel deadline at 5pm on Monday.
It is believed the new offer, which would value the company close to £1bn, could be tabled to Betfair’s board as early as Sunday. But sources this weekend stressed that conversations were still ongoing and that a final decision had not been made.
It is believed CVC, the owner of Formula 1, will come back with a sweetened proposal, above last month’s 880p-a-share approach, in order to gain access to Betfair’s books.
However, the new price is expected to be short of the £10 a share analysts say CVC will have to pay out to be in with a shot of succeeding in its offer.
Shares in the group, which floated in October 2010 at £13 a share, closed on Friday at 898p, up 2.63pc, valuing the company at £936m.
