Our conscience is clear over tax and profits, says Thames Water
Britain's biggest water company Thames Water has declared its conscience “absolutely clear”, after Ofwat chairman Jonson Cox claimed some utilities’ profits and tax-reducing corporate structures were “morally questionable”. Ofwat has already asked water companies to look at ways of sharing windfall gains with consumers. Photo: Abbie Trayler-Smith/Telegraph	By Emily Gosden
11:56AM BST 10 Jun 2013
Follow Comments
Privately-owned Thames, which serves 14m customers across London and the south of England, paid no corporation tax this year and has faced criticism by MPs and campaigners over its tax arrangements. Speaking as the company unveiled a plunge in annual profits, Stuart Siddall, Thames Water finance director denied that the company was avoiding paying tax and said: “We have an absolutely clear conscience about everything we are doing. "Everything is transparent. We are reviewed by HMRC every year as a major corporation and we are seen as low-risk because our tax is very straightforward."
In the year to March 2013 Thames’s pre-tax profits fell 35pc to £144.9m owing to bad weather, unpaid customer bills and rising energy costs. The company booked a £5.1m tax credit and said that although it paid no corporation tax it paid business rates and other taxes which amounted to about £150m. The company said: “We have not paid much corporation tax in recent years because the Government’s tax system allows us to delay, not avoid, payment of tax based on how much we invest. Because we are investing £1bn a year from 2010 to 2015, more than any water firm in the UK’s history, we are able to defer a lot of tax payments to future years.”
