Writing in the Telegraph today Mr Cox said that some water companies’ use of high-coupon loans to shareholders to reduce their tax liability was “morally questionable” and noted criticism of “complex offshore holding structures”. He said companies must share windfall returns with consumers and pledged to “lift the veil” on corporate practices, claiming he was yet to find an unlisted water company that fully complied with the UK Corporate Governance Code “or satisfactorily explains why not”. Mr Siddall said Thames had taken further steps to make sure its accounts were "very transparent" and gave "good reasons" for not complying with parts of the code over the number of non-executive directors on its board. "[Mr Cox] won't have seen our accounts today but I think if he reads our accounts he will find that everywhere we have either complied or explained," he said. "We haven’t left a stone unturned in making sure we have done that.”
Defending its profits, Mr Siddall said: "We need to make a sensible return because we have to service our debt and attract equity into the business. Our return this year was 4.31pc which is below what was determined by Ofwat."
Thames Water said its shareholders bore the £17m costs of drought and flooding and were "exposed to these risks so our customers do not have to be". Thames Water’s accounts show it paid £231.4m in dividends to parent company Kemble Water Holdings, down from £279.5m, due to the “dip in financial performance”. It paid £92m to its ultimate shareholders, which include funds from Australia, China, Abu Dhabi and Britain, down from £200m last year after paying no distribution in the second half of the year. Of that £92m, £74.5m was paid as a dividend, after tax, while £17.5m was paid as interest on an 11pc-rate Eurobond loan to its shareholders. “That would be tax deductible in our books but our shareholders would pay tax on that," Mr Siddall said. "It is only £17.5m. It's effectively a proxy for dividends; if they didn't have that they would receive dividends. It's part of the corporate structure and whoever receive that interest will pay tax on it."
Thames Water’s accounts also show it paid £328.2m interest on “intercompany loans”, which Mr Siddall said was paid via a Cayman Islands funding vehicle to its external bondholders such as pension funds. However, he said the funding vehicle was “registered in the UK for tax” and there was “no tax advantage” as a result. “The Cayman Island companies are there purely to comply with UK company law requirements for the acquisition financing structure,” he said. Utilities
